revision.text:
An '''active chromatin sequence''' (ACS) is a region of [[DNA]] in a [[eukaryote|eukaryotic]] [[chromosome]] in which [[histone]] modifications such as [[acetylation]] lead to exposure of the [[DNA sequence]] thus allowing binding of [[transcription factors]] and [[Transcription (genetics)|transcription]] to take place. Active chromatin may also be called [[euchromatin]]. ACSs may occur in non-expressed gene regions which are assumed to be "poised" for [[gene transcription|transcription]]. The sequence once exposed often contains a promoter to began transcription. At this site [[acetylation]] or [[methylation]] can take place causing a conformational change to the chromatin. At the active chromatin sequence site deacetylation can caused the gene to be repressed if not being expressed.

